5) What is Cloudfront?\par
\b0\f0\fs24\lang9\tab Amazon CloudFront is a content delivery network (CDN) provided by Amazon Web Services (AWS). It is a global service that delivers static and dynamic web content, including videos, images, and other media, to users with low latency and high transfer speeds.\par
\tab CloudFront works by caching content in multiple edge locations around the world, which are distributed across different geographic regions. When a user requests content, CloudFront routes the request to the edge location nearest to the user, reducing the latency and improving the response time.\par
\par
\tab CloudFront can be used to deliver content from a variety of sources, including Amazon S3, EC2 instances, and on-premises servers, as well as from third-party services. CloudFront also provides a range of features such as SSL/TLS encryption, access control, and real-time logs, making it a highly secure and reliable service.\par
\par
\tab CloudFront can be integrated with other AWS services, such as Amazon Route 53, AWS Lambda, and AWS WAF, to provide a comprehensive and scalable solution for content delivery and protection.\par
\par
\b 6) Implement CLoudfront to s3 bucket and configure cloudfront domain to R53?\par
\par
\b0 1) Create an S3 bucket\par
2)Create a new CloudFront distribution by going to the CloudFront console and clicking on "Create Distribution".\par
3)Select "Web" as the delivery method and click on "Get Started".\par
4)In the "Origin Domain Name" field, select your S3 bucket from the dropdown list.\par
5)Configure the other CloudFront settings, such as "Viewer Protocol Policy", "Allowed HTTP Methods", "Price Class", etc. as per your requirements.\par
6)Click on "Create Distribution" to create your CloudFront distribution.\par
7)Once the distribution is created, note down the CloudFront domain name that is created for your distribution.\par
8)Go to the Route 53 console and create a new record set for your domain name, selecting "Alias" as the record type.\par
9)In the "Alias Target" field, paste the CloudFront domain name that you noted down in Step 7.\par
10)Save the record set and wait for the DNS propagation to complete.\par
\par
\tab bOnce the DNS propagation is complete, your CloudFront distribution will be configured to serve your content from your S3 bucket, and your CloudFront domain name will be mapped to your Route 53 record set, enabling users to access your content using your custom domain name.\par
